, 58.-4. We may observe the transition from the periodic to the detached style—the latter, as frequently, being characterised by much asyndeton. This often occurs where a narrative is to be given. The events, instead of being grouped by subordination os clauses, are co- ordinated, their connection and relative importance being indicated, in the main, simply by the order of their recital. Thus the verbs fall singly like the strokes of a hammer:l the general impression left upon the mind is that of a drama very rapidly enacted, or proceeding by stmdy movement to a catastrophe ; or it is that of a story accurately exhibited in its details, to conciliate acceptance.
